snippet.textDisplay: Watching this trailer does not make me want to see this film, it appears to be another: America wins the war movie. Again? What I see here looks too formula, too comic book. WWII had been going on for 3 years. The two best movies about the war at sea in the Atlantic are The Cruel Sea (1952) and Das Boot (1981). Even my favourite American movie about the sea war, The Enemy Below (1957) I found out later was loosely based on a novel by Denys Rayner, a British naval officer and participant in the Battle of the Atlantic; in the book, the ship is British, in the movie American. That's not to say there aren't good U.S. war movies/series: Saving Private Ryan (1997) and Band of Brothers (2001) are great.

snippet.textDisplay: In the summer of 1944, my father was in the 97th Infantry Division being transported to France in a convoy.  From the Mid-Atlantic to France, the convoy was under constant attack.  My dad’s unit was on an old Italian freighter that was starting to leak. snippet.textOriginal: In the summer of 1944, my father was in the 97th Infantry Division being transported to France in a convoy.  From the Mid-Atlantic to France, the convoy was under constant attack.  My dad’s unit was on an old Italian freighter that was starting to leak.  When they arrived in the port of Le Harve France, the ship sank in the harbor.
